WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.868 --> 00:00:04.537
ENRIQUE CABALLERO: In the
United States, it is estimated

00:00:04.570 --> 00:00:06.806
that there's
about 100 million people

00:00:06.839 --> 00:00:09.042
with diabetes and prediabetes--

00:00:09.075 --> 00:00:12.145
100 million people
in the country

00:00:12.178 --> 00:00:14.047
affected by
a blood sugar problem.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:18.351
KELLY CLOSE: The economic impact
of diabetes is devastating.

00:00:18.384 --> 00:00:21.487
We spent almost $350 billion

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:23.890
on diabetes in the
United States last year.

00:00:23.923 --> 00:00:27.460
NARRATOR: Diabetes--
a chronic disease

00:00:27.493 --> 00:00:30.463
that's notoriously
difficult to control.

00:00:30.496 --> 00:00:33.466
It can maim and even kill.

00:00:33.499 --> 00:00:35.835
A generation ago,

00:00:35.868 --> 00:00:40.406
less than three percent
of Americans had diabetes.

00:00:40.439 --> 00:00:43.976
Today, it's almost ten percent.

00:00:44.009 --> 00:00:45.578
It is now predicted

00:00:45.611 --> 00:00:49.849
that half of the U.S. population

00:00:49.882 --> 00:00:54.787
will have either diabetes
or pre-diabetes

00:00:54.820 --> 00:00:57.490
by the year 2025.

00:00:57.523 --> 00:01:00.493
Half!

00:01:00.526 --> 00:01:02.795
NARRATOR:
Living with diabetes today

00:01:02.828 --> 00:01:04.697
is a story of new discoveries

00:01:04.730 --> 00:01:08.634
about our food environments
and choices.

00:01:08.667 --> 00:01:12.138
As a seven-year-old coming
from a Third-World country

00:01:12.171 --> 00:01:14.006
and getting free candy,
I was, like,

00:01:14.039 --> 00:01:16.709
"Yo, I'm so down
for America right now.

00:01:16.742 --> 00:01:18.077
Like, this is tight."

00:01:18.110 --> 00:01:21.981
NARRATOR: It builds
on exciting new progress

00:01:22.014 --> 00:01:24.951
in drugs and technologies

00:01:24.984 --> 00:01:28.454
that have made the disease
more manageable.

00:01:28.487 --> 00:01:29.755
This device
is around the corner,

00:01:29.788 --> 00:01:30.890
and that's really
what we're trying to do,

00:01:30.923 --> 00:01:32.625
is get much better therapy
to people

00:01:32.658 --> 00:01:34.627
that requires much less
of their participation

00:01:34.660 --> 00:01:36.195
and provides much better care.

00:01:36.228 --> 00:01:39.899
NARRATOR: And it reveals
the terrible struggles

00:01:39.932 --> 00:01:43.236
that so many with diabetes
still have,

00:01:43.269 --> 00:01:45.638
day in and day out.

00:01:45.671 --> 00:01:48.307
So, they was looking at me,
like,

00:01:48.340 --> 00:01:51.077
"How are you even standing here
on your feet?

00:01:51.110 --> 00:01:52.678
You're supposed to be
in a coma."

00:01:52.711 --> 00:01:56.849
CLOSE: So when we think
about the impact to the system--

00:01:56.882 --> 00:01:59.519
way too many
emergency-room visits,

00:01:59.552 --> 00:02:02.021
way too many amputations--

00:02:02.054 --> 00:02:06.492
why isn't there
a war on diabetes?

00:02:06.525 --> 00:02:10.663
♪ ♪

00:02:15.367 --> 00:02:18.971
(siren blaring)

00:02:19.004 --> 00:02:20.406
WOMAN: She got her flu shot
already.

00:02:20.439 --> 00:02:23.643
So, this guy, I was just told...
no, then he's fine, okay.

00:02:23.676 --> 00:02:24.744
We're good.

00:02:24.777 --> 00:02:26.546
Okay, let's put Goodall
in a room

00:02:26.579 --> 00:02:27.813
and I'll have my nurse
practitioner start with him.

00:02:27.846 --> 00:02:29.048
Thank you.
WOMAN: That's good.

00:02:29.081 --> 00:02:30.082
DEAN SCHILLINGER:
I'm Dean Schillinger.

00:02:30.115 --> 00:02:31.918
I'm a primary care doctor

00:02:31.951 --> 00:02:34.520
at San Francisco
General Hospital.

00:02:34.553 --> 00:02:36.422
One minute, okay?
WOMAN: Okay.

00:02:36.455 --> 00:02:38.357
SCHILLINGER: When I started out
as a young doctor,

00:02:38.390 --> 00:02:43.663 line:0%
about one in 20 of my patients
had type 2 diabetes.

00:02:43.696 --> 00:02:46.899 line:0%
Now it's one in two.

00:02:46.932 --> 00:02:50.403 line:0%
NARRATOR: Diabetes undercuts one
of the most basic functions

00:02:50.436 --> 00:02:51.704
of our bodies--

00:02:51.737 --> 00:02:55.641
our ability to break food down
into nutrients,

00:02:55.674 --> 00:03:00.313
including the sugar glucose
that provides energy.

00:03:00.346 --> 00:03:01.681
- Okay.

00:03:01.714 --> 00:03:06.152
NARRATOR: The hormone that
manages sugar levels is insulin.

00:03:06.185 --> 00:03:09.355
♪ ♪

00:03:09.388 --> 00:03:12.792 line:0%
So, think of insulin
as the medicine

00:03:12.825 --> 00:03:15.895 line:0%
that you can't live without,
right?

00:03:15.928 --> 00:03:19.265
Like a key that unlocks
the door to your cells

00:03:19.298 --> 00:03:21.701
and allows the glucose
to enter your cells.

00:03:21.734 --> 00:03:23.970
That keeps the level of sugar
in your blood in check

00:03:24.003 --> 00:03:26.472
and your cells nourished.

00:03:26.505 --> 00:03:28.507
NARRATOR:
This insulin-glucose cycle

00:03:28.540 --> 00:03:31.711
is disrupted in diabetes.

00:03:31.744 --> 00:03:33.446
In type 1 diabetes,

00:03:33.479 --> 00:03:36.182
the immune system
attacks and destroys

00:03:36.215 --> 00:03:40.186
the part of the pancreas
that makes insulin.

00:03:40.219 --> 00:03:43.990
In type 2, the pancreas makes
too little insulin,

00:03:44.023 --> 00:03:48.661
and the body resists
the insulin it has.

00:03:48.694 --> 00:03:49.862
CLOSE:
It's really obvious

00:03:49.895 --> 00:03:51.230
when your blood glucose
is too low,

00:03:51.263 --> 00:03:53.065
why that's dangerous.

00:03:53.098 --> 00:03:55.668
You know, you can't breathe,
you can't survive.

00:03:55.701 --> 00:03:57.837
Um, you won't live very long

00:03:57.870 --> 00:04:00.539
if you have blood sugar
that's too low.

00:04:00.572 --> 00:04:02.642
Blood sugar that's too high
is equally dangerous,

00:04:02.675 --> 00:04:04.677
if not more dangerous over time.

00:04:04.710 --> 00:04:08.281 line:0%
Diabetes is truly
a silent disease.

00:04:08.314 --> 00:04:10.816 line:0%
It could take up to 15 years

00:04:10.849 --> 00:04:14.787
for someone with diabetes
to develop the first symptoms

00:04:14.820 --> 00:04:17.023
that are related
to high blood-sugar levels.

00:04:17.056 --> 00:04:21.627
You don't have a water and soap,
you want to use an alcohol pad.

00:04:21.660 --> 00:04:25.698
NARRATOR: For many people, by
the time diabetes is diagnosed,

00:04:25.731 --> 00:04:27.099
the damage is done--

00:04:27.132 --> 00:04:31.337
damage that can include
blindness, heart disease,

00:04:31.370 --> 00:04:36.309
strokes, even amputations.
NURSE: All right.

00:04:36.342 --> 00:04:37.943
There's not a lot of things
more disfiguring

00:04:37.976 --> 00:04:43.015
than, than losing a limb,
particularly a leg or a foot.

00:04:43.048 --> 00:04:44.550
We now have a limb-salvage unit

00:04:44.583 --> 00:04:46.352
at San Francisco
General Hospital

00:04:46.385 --> 00:04:50.156
to handle the volume
of these amputation patients,

00:04:50.189 --> 00:04:53.659
something ten years ago
would have been unheard of.

00:04:53.692 --> 00:04:56.329
I've probably seen maybe
a thousand amputations.

00:04:56.362 --> 00:04:57.863
As far as these things go,

00:04:57.896 --> 00:04:59.632
it's healed really well.
- Yeah.

00:04:59.665 --> 00:05:01.133
- And it looks good.

00:05:01.166 --> 00:05:04.704
NARRATOR:
Dr. Schillinger's next patient

00:05:04.737 --> 00:05:10.476
