deserves the best patient.

00:08:12.491 --> 00:08:14.059
- Exactly.
- That's how it goes.

00:08:14.092 --> 00:08:16.395
- And I was going to say that.

00:08:16.428 --> 00:08:18.664
- See, great minds
even think alike, too.

00:08:18.697 --> 00:08:20.132
- So, so we got,
that's the clinic,

00:08:20.165 --> 00:08:21.400
like, your primary care doctor.

00:08:21.433 --> 00:08:23.202
I will become
your primary care doctor.

00:08:23.235 --> 00:08:24.904
- Okay.
- Okay, my friend.

00:08:24.937 --> 00:08:26.539
- Appreciate you.
- You, too, good luck.

00:08:26.572 --> 00:08:27.540
- Thanks a lot.

00:08:27.573 --> 00:08:29.942
♪ ♪

00:08:29.975 --> 00:08:31.443
SCHILLINGER:
I talked to the surgeon,

00:08:31.476 --> 00:08:34.513
and we both felt it was kind of
like a 50/50 proposition

00:08:34.546 --> 00:08:36.982
as to whether he was
going to lose his toe or not.

00:08:37.015 --> 00:08:40.286
It would really be dependent
on his behavior, his choices.

00:08:40.319 --> 00:08:42.021
Would he stay off the foot,

00:08:42.054 --> 00:08:44.023
like, completely off the foot?

00:08:44.056 --> 00:08:46.992
Would he elevate the foot
higher than his heart?

00:08:47.025 --> 00:08:50.963
Would he take the antibiotics
correctly and to completion?

00:08:50.996 --> 00:08:52.498
Would he manage his diabetes?

00:08:52.531 --> 00:08:55.067
Because that's perfect
for the bugs to keep growing--

00:08:55.100 --> 00:08:56.535
they love the sugar.

00:08:56.568 --> 00:08:58.404
So, it was a lot of ifs.

00:08:58.437 --> 00:09:01.407
So, um...

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:05.678
You know, this is a fairly
typical amputation story.

00:09:05.711 --> 00:09:07.613
I mean, it's...

00:09:07.646 --> 00:09:08.948
