00:09:08.981 --> 00:09:10.683
The only thing that differs is

00:09:10.716 --> 00:09:12.618
the person with the foot.

00:09:12.651 --> 00:09:16.388
And in this case,
he's a very unique individual,

00:09:16.421 --> 00:09:18.057
as many people are, but he's,

00:09:18.090 --> 00:09:19.592
I think he's, he's very special.

00:09:19.625 --> 00:09:22.861
WOMAN:
All right, here we go.

00:09:22.894 --> 00:09:28.100
SCHILLINGER: If he can find
that story in himself...

00:09:28.133 --> 00:09:31.303 line:0%
LEE: This is so awesome,
I haven't smelled air in a week.

00:09:31.336 --> 00:09:33.272 line:0%
SCHILLINGER: ...I do believe
that this experience,

00:09:33.305 --> 00:09:35.541
as, as terrible as it is,

00:09:35.574 --> 00:09:38.444
actually may be
transformative for him.

00:09:38.477 --> 00:09:39.945
It could go south, too.

00:09:39.978 --> 00:09:42.048
(people talking in background)

00:09:44.016 --> 00:09:45.384
DAN HURLEY:
150 years ago,

00:09:45.417 --> 00:09:48.354 line:0%
a doctor could go
most of their career

00:09:48.387 --> 00:09:51.590 line:0%
and maybe see one or two people
with diabetes.

00:09:51.623 --> 00:09:55.794
It was just considered
a very rare disease,

00:09:55.827 --> 00:09:59.465
and it had been
since ancient times.

00:09:59.498 --> 00:10:03.469
NARRATOR: Records of diabetes
may go back to the pharaohs.

00:10:03.502 --> 00:10:06.405
This papyrus describes
treating the disease

00:10:06.438 --> 00:10:11.343
with seeds, honey,
and yellow ochre clay.

00:10:11.376 --> 00:10:14.847
There were no better treatments
until 1921,

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:17.249
when insulin was discovered.

00:10:17.282 --> 00:10:20.819
But insulin was still
a treatment, not a cure.

00:10:20.852 --> 00:10:24.089
Even with new,
more effective drug formulas,

00:10:24.122 --> 00:10:25.991 line:0%
in the last two decades,

00:10:26.024 --> 00:10:31.163 line:0%
rates of both type 1 and type 2
have skyrocketed.

00:10:31.196 --> 00:10:37.603
Everybody knows that type 2
diabetes has been increasing.

00:10:37.636 --> 00:10:42.007
What people don't get
is that type 1--

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:45.310
it used to be called
childhood-onset diabetes--

00:10:45.343 --> 00:10:50.949
has been increasing
at the same rate.

00:10:50.982 --> 00:10:53.986
When I developed
type 1 diabetes in 1975,

00:10:54.019 --> 00:10:56.689
I didn't meet anyone else

00:10:56.722 --> 00:10:59.692
who had that disease
at my college.

00:10:59.725 --> 00:11:00.959
I didn't meet friends,

00:11:00.992 --> 00:11:04.163
I didn't have family
who had type 1 diabetes.

00:11:04.196 --> 00:11:08.634
Today, I know so many people
with type 1

00:11:08.667 --> 00:11:11.203
not because I wrote
a book about it,

00:11:11.236 --> 00:11:13.539
but my neighbor down the block,

00:11:13.572 --> 00:11:15.007
the, the girl around the corner,

00:11:15.040 --> 00:11:18.544
the editor of my local paper,
the priest at my church.

00:11:21.480 --> 00:11:25.284
NICOLE: My name's Nicole,
and I'm a type 1 diabetic.

00:11:25.317 --> 00:11:26.885
People always say,
"You're type 1.

00:11:26.918 --> 00:11:28.087
Is that the kind that's worse?"

00:11:28.120 --> 00:11:30.989
Well, I have diabetes
complications,

00:11:31.022 --> 00:11:32.391
and from where I'm sitting,

00:11:32.424 --> 00:11:34.059
it doesn't matter
if you're type 1 or type 2,

00:11:34.092 --> 00:11:37.262
both type 1 diabetics
and type 2 diabetics

00:11:37.295 --> 00:11:38.630
can get complications.

00:11:38.663 --> 00:11:41.133
And they're
the same complications.

00:11:41.166 --> 00:11:43.035
NARRATOR: The complications
in diabetes

00:11:43.068 --> 00:11:45.137
tend to accumulate slowly,

00:11:45.170 --> 00:11:49.408 line:0%
as the extra blood sugar
damages the eyes, the heart,

00:11:49.441 --> 00:11:51.176 line:0%
other organs bit by bit.

