NICOLE: So, basically,
my blood sugar is in the 90s

00:11:54.012 --> 00:11:57.249 line:0%
and is trending down,
so that's what I'm watching.

00:11:57.282 --> 00:11:59.518
NARRATOR:
For type 1s,

00:11:59.551 --> 00:12:03.856
the complications can also be
immediate and disastrous.

00:12:03.889 --> 00:12:08.160
The pancreas is
no longer making insulin.

00:12:08.193 --> 00:12:12.498
Sugar is not getting out of
the blood and into the cells.

00:12:12.531 --> 00:12:19.404
Your body is designed to have
blood sugar at a perfect level.

00:12:19.437 --> 00:12:20.973
It's really incredible

00:12:21.006 --> 00:12:24.076
how well the healthy body
regulates

00:12:24.109 --> 00:12:25.744
the blood-sugar level--

00:12:25.777 --> 00:12:27.679
not too high, not too low.

00:12:27.712 --> 00:12:32.484
I think that no one prepares you
for, mentally,

00:12:32.517 --> 00:12:34.419
what it's going to take to live
with something

00:12:34.452 --> 00:12:36.288
that's so 24/7.

00:12:36.321 --> 00:12:38.090
- Wonderful.

00:12:38.123 --> 00:12:42.060
NICOLE: I've had diabetes
for 18 years,

00:12:42.093 --> 00:12:44.496
and you always have to be
thinking.

00:12:44.529 --> 00:12:46.031
You have to think

00:12:46.064 --> 00:12:48.367
before you exercise--
"What's your blood sugar?"

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:50.235
Before you go to sleep,
"What's your blood sugar?"

00:12:50.268 --> 00:12:52.304
In the middle of the night,
"What's your blood sugar?"

00:12:52.337 --> 00:12:54.039
When you're sick,
"What's your blood sugar?

00:12:54.072 --> 00:12:57.075
You know,
it, it never escapes you.

00:12:57.108 --> 00:12:58.977
♪ ♪

00:12:59.010 --> 00:13:00.646
NARRATOR:
Nicole's diagnosis started

00:13:00.679 --> 00:13:02.848
with the classic symptoms
of diabetes,

00:13:02.881 --> 00:13:06.685
so well known
that a 17th-century physician

00:13:06.718 --> 00:13:11.256
called the disease
"the pissing evil."

00:13:11.289 --> 00:13:13.959
I had to pee all the time,
and I was drinking a lot.

00:13:13.992 --> 00:13:15.427
And I remember telling
one of my friends,

00:13:15.460 --> 00:13:17.830
I said, I was, like, "There's
something wrong with me."

00:13:17.863 --> 00:13:21.166
I was drinking,
it's like you're in a desert,

00:13:21.199 --> 00:13:23.235
and you are...

00:13:23.268 --> 00:13:26.438
You're so thirsty, like,
you can't stop.

00:13:26.471 --> 00:13:30.175
From there,
I was telling my mom.

00:13:30.208 --> 00:13:32.444
She was, like,
"I think we need to get you

00:13:32.477 --> 00:13:34.046
tested for diabetes."

00:13:34.079 --> 00:13:35.914
And I was, like,
"Diabetes, what's that?"

00:13:35.947 --> 00:13:37.282
I didn't know what it was.

00:13:37.315 --> 00:13:38.417
And she's just, like,

00:13:38.450 --> 00:13:40.252
"We need to take you
to the doctor."

00:13:40.285 --> 00:13:41.420
And she took me,

00:13:41.453 --> 00:13:44.189
and right away,
they diagnosed me with diabetes,

00:13:44.222 --> 00:13:47.659
and they started me on insulin
within days.

00:13:47.692 --> 00:13:49.695
I actually, I didn't end up
in a coma.

00:13:49.728 --> 00:13:51.897
A lot of people will end up
in a diabetic coma

00:13:51.930 --> 00:13:53.832
and have to be hospitalized.

00:13:53.865 --> 00:13:57.603
I think my blood sugar was,
like, maybe 375-ish,

00:13:57.636 --> 00:13:58.904
somewhere around there.

00:13:58.937 --> 00:14:02.474
So it wasn't you know, 800-plus.

00:14:02.507 --> 00:14:05.477
So, I got lucky, so, yeah.

00:14:07.212 --> 00:14:12.184
When you get diagnosed at 17,
it's hard.

00:14:12.217 --> 00:14:16.555
I was so afraid to go low
that I kept myself high.

00:14:16.588 --> 00:14:19.925
Because low blood sugars to me
meant I could die,

00:14:19.958 --> 00:14:22.261
and specifically,
I could die in the night,

00:14:22.294 --> 00:14:23.595
like, when I'm sleeping.

00:14:23.628 --> 00:14:29.902
I am unconscious every night
when I go to sleep,

00:14:29.935 --> 00:14:34.339
and I can't know
what my blood-sugar level is.

00:14:34.372 --> 00:14:38.977
One time, I was alone
with our daughter,

00:14:39.010 --> 00:14:41.280
who was then
about eight years old,

00:14:41.313 --> 00:14:46.218
and she found me
sweating profusely

00:14:46.251 --> 00:14:49.321
and unable to come to.

00:14:49.354 --> 00:14:52.491
And she realized something
was very, very wrong with me.

00:14:52.524 --> 00:14:54.760
She didn't know
what she was supposed to do.

00:14:54.793 --> 00:14:55.961
She wasn't quite sure.

00:14:55.994 --> 00:14:58.063
She knew I needed
something "sweet."

00:14:58.096 --> 00:15:03.135
So, she went into the kitchen
and got marshmallow fluff

00:15:03.168 --> 00:15:07.039
and began spooning it
into my mouth.

00:15:07.072 --> 00:15:09.909
And she saved my life.

00:15:13.878 --> 00:15:15.580
NICOLE: Someone
that doesn't have diabetes,

00:15:15.613 --> 00:15:17.215
their blood sugars are stable.

00:15:17.248 --> 00:15:20.519
They're consistent, just
kind of like a line like this.

00:15:20.552 --> 00:15:24.389
But, with me, my blood sugar
could be up, down.

00:15:24.422 --> 00:15:28.093
So, when it's up, it's high,
and when it's down, it's low,

00:15:28.126 --> 00:15:31.296
and so the low blood sugars
can make me potentially

00:15:31.329 --> 00:15:32.965
go into a diabetic coma.

00:15:32.998 --> 00:15:34.433
And I was terrified.

00:15:34.466 --> 00:15:36.501
So, I'd just, oh,
eat a bunch, you know,

00:15:36.534 --> 00:15:39.738
right before I go to sleep,
and I'd be fine.

00:15:41.106 --> 00:15:44.443
I think it was
deep-rooted denial.

00:15:44.476 --> 00:15:46.345
♪ ♪

00:15:46.378 --> 00:15:50.716
I skipped insulin injections.

00:15:50.749 --> 00:15:53.151
I ate whatever I wanted.

00:15:53.184 --> 00:15:56.655
I pretended
like I wasn't a diabetic.

00:15:56.688 --> 00:16:01.994
I now have a list
of diabetes complications,

00:16:02.027 --> 00:16:05.230
to include kidney disease,

00:16:05.263 --> 00:16:08.367
which turned
into kidney failure,

00:16:08.400 --> 00:16:11.670
which turned into,
now I am a dialysis patient.

00:16:11.703 --> 00:16:15.273
I have to go to dialysis
three times a week

00:16:15.306 --> 00:16:18.343
and have my blood filtered out.

00:16:18.376 --> 00:16:21.480
If I don't do those things,
I'll die.

00:16:21.513 --> 00:16:25.617
One of my least favorite
complications,

00:16:25.650 --> 00:16:28.453
I have severe diabetic
proliferative retinopathy,

00:16:28.486 --> 00:16:30.622
which is end-stage eye disease.

00:16:30.655 --> 00:16:33.492
That's the kind
that steals vision.

00:16:33.525 --> 00:16:35.127
And I don't know what's scarier,

00:16:35.160 --> 00:16:38.363
my eyes or my kidney...

00:16:38.396 --> 00:16:41.233
I guess the kidney disease
is what scares me the most,

00:16:41.266 --> 00:16:44.970
because, you know,
the longer you're on dialysis,

00:16:45.003 --> 00:16:47.706
the more the death rate
statistically goes up.

00:16:49.240 --> 00:16:51.510
NARRATOR:
With no functioning kidneys

00:16:51.543 --> 00:16:53.445
and a damaged pancreas,

00:16:53.478 --> 00:16:56.548
Nicole is now in line
to replace both,

00:16:56.581 --> 00:16:59.251
a rare dual transplant.

00:17:01.286 --> 00:17:04.389
For now, she's doing
everything she can

00:17:04.422 --> 00:17:06.358
to stay alive and be ready,

00:17:06.391 --> 00:17:09.294
if donor organs
become available.

00:17:09.327 --> 00:17:12.330
♪ ♪

00:17:12.363 --> 00:17:14.199
NICOLE:
Now that I have kidney failure,

00:17:14.232 --> 00:17:16.401
I also have to watch what I eat.

00:17:16.434 --> 00:17:22.140
I have to now watch
potassium, sodium, phosphorus,

00:17:22.173 --> 00:17:25.010
and vegetables
contain those things.

00:17:25.043 --> 00:17:27.913
So, I actually have a chart.

00:17:27.946 --> 00:17:30.649
Avocados, bananas--
I don't eat those at all.

00:17:30.682 --> 00:17:32.050
That's, I just don't
touch those.

00:17:32.083 --> 00:17:34.519
If I eat too much potassium,

00:17:34.552 --> 00:17:35.987
it could stop my heart
and I can die.

00:17:36.020 --> 00:17:37.956
So, that's why I don't
eat potatoes anymore.

00:17:40.125 --> 00:17:44.196
I got yelled at
for eating too much kale.

00:17:44.229 --> 00:17:45.630
And they're, like, "Do you
want this to jeopardize...?"

00:17:45.663 --> 00:17:46.932
I'm, like, "Whoa."

00:17:46.965 --> 00:17:48.200
I'm, like, "Okay,
no leafy greens, I got it."

00:17:51.436 --> 00:17:55.240
If I could tell
my 17-year-old self,

00:17:55.273 --> 00:17:57.709
my newly diagnosed self,
something, it would be,

00:17:57.742 --> 00:18:02.047
"Do everything that the
doctors, professionals, say.

00:18:02.080 --> 00:18:06.451
It's not worth it not to."

00:18:06.484 --> 00:18:09.054
CLOSE:
So it's so possible

00:18:09.087 --> 00:18:11.823
to live a long and
healthy life with diabetes.

00:18:11.856 --> 00:18:13.492
It's possible by thinking

00:18:13.525 --> 00:18:16.828
about how, how do we keep
our tanks full?

00:18:16.861 --> 00:18:18.430
How do we be our best selves?

00:18:18.463 --> 00:18:22.000
I've had type 1 diabetes
for almost 35 years,

00:18:22.033 --> 00:18:25.137
and I have kids and a husband
and a great job.

00:18:25.170 --> 00:18:28.240
A lot of people with
either type 1 or type 2

00:18:28.273 --> 00:18:29.774
live well with the disease.

00:18:29.807 --> 00:18:33.612
They're singers and actors and
professional sports figures

00:18:33.645 --> 00:18:35.580
and major businesspeople
and political figures.

00:18:35.613 --> 00:18:38.316
There's even a race-car driver
with diabetes.

00:18:38.349 --> 00:18:40.852
But it takes constant attention,

00:18:40.885 --> 00:18:44.723
because it's a complicated
and chronic disease.

00:18:44.756 --> 00:18:46.525
LEE:
I come from a rough background.

00:18:46.558 --> 00:18:49.828
Back in those days,

00:18:49.861 --> 00:18:51.296
we'd run out of food.

00:18:51.329 --> 00:18:55.300
We was eating syrup sandwiches,
sugar sandwiches,

00:18:55.333 --> 00:18:57.836
when you just take the syrup
and put it on the bread.

00:19:00.605 --> 00:19:04.376
Drunk Hawaiian Punch, Capri
Suns, all that type of stuff.

00:19:04.409 --> 00:19:08.713
I'm a junk-food addict--
I eat candy, all type of sweets.

00:19:08.746 --> 00:19:11.583
It's been a real battle
and a real struggle to where,

00:19:11.616 --> 00:19:14.286
now, I'm at this point,

00:19:14.319 --> 00:19:19.491
from not being able
to control bad habits.

00:19:19.524 --> 00:19:21.193
♪ ♪

00:19:21.226 --> 00:19:24.095
NARRATOR: Do bad habits
cause type 2 diabetes?

00:19:24.128 --> 00:19:29.134
Not everyone who consumes a
lot of sugar gets the disease.

00:19:29.167 --> 00:19:34.306
But sugary drinks and foods are
certainly a part of the problem.

00:19:34.339 --> 00:19:36.808
♪ ♪

00:19:36.841 --> 00:19:39.711
Some companies target
communities of color

00:19:39.744 --> 00:19:42.914
with ads for sodas
and high-sugar snacks,

00:19:42.947 --> 00:19:44.616
and these are the communities

00:19:44.649 --> 00:19:47.919
with the highest
diabetes levels.

00:19:47.952 --> 00:19:50.989
ANTHONY HATCH:
We know an awful lot

00:19:51.022 --> 00:19:52.357 line:0%
about the environmental
conditions

00:19:52.390 --> 00:19:54.693 line:0%
that lead to dramatically
increased prevalence

00:19:54.726 --> 00:19:55.927 line:0%
of type 2 diabetes.

00:19:55.960 --> 00:19:59.364
It's living
in sugar-rich environments,

00:19:59.397 --> 00:20:04.169
where people have inequitable
access to healthful food,

00:20:04.202 --> 00:20:07.839
where people are living
increasingly sedentary lives.

00:20:07.872 --> 00:20:11.009
These are the true causes
of not just diabetes,

00:20:11.042 --> 00:20:12.711
but of chronic disease
in general.

00:20:32.830 --> 00:20:35.667
LEE: For me, honestly,
it's overwhelming,

00:20:35.700 --> 00:20:37.869
but I have to...

00:20:37.902 --> 00:20:41.172
It's not like
I can get around it

00:20:41.205 --> 00:20:43.341
without taking care of it.

00:20:43.374 --> 00:20:47.813
So, I'm just dealing with it
the best way I can.

00:21:00.458 --> 00:21:02.260
So now, waking up every day,

00:21:02.293 --> 00:21:04.396
having to check blood

00:21:04.429 --> 00:21:07.499
and make sure these levels
are correct

00:21:07.532 --> 00:21:09.534
and all this different stuff.

00:21:11.502 --> 00:21:14.606
I'm trying my best here.

00:21:14.639 --> 00:21:17.008
Yeah, the more I do this,
I'm getting better.

00:21:17.041 --> 00:21:19.277
I watched the doctors do this,

00:21:19.310 --> 00:21:22.113
so now I'm trying to...

00:21:22.146 --> 00:21:26.718
be just as good as them
wrapping it.

00:21:26.751 --> 00:21:33.425
♪ ♪

00:21:33.458 --> 00:21:34.493
(talks softly)

00:21:36.794 --> 00:21:39.097
(exhales)

00:21:39.130 --> 00:21:43.635
NARRATOR: Almost all people
with diabetes, 95%,

00:21:43.668 --> 00:21:47.272
are type 2, like Monteil.

00:21:47.305 --> 00:21:51.276
The remaining five percent
are type 1.

00:21:51.309 --> 00:21:52.844
But what sets off the disease?

00:21:52.877 --> 00:21:56.781
Type 1 is genetic,
perhaps triggered by a virus

00:21:56.814 --> 00:22:01.186
or other environmental factors.

00:22:01.219 --> 00:22:04.622
Type 2 is triggered
by many factors:

00:22:04.655 --> 00:22:07.292
the person's genes,
their environment,

00:22:07.325 --> 00:22:11.796
getting too little exercise,
gaining too much weight,

00:22:11.829 --> 00:22:15.333
eating too much
unhealthy, sugary foods.

00:22:15.366 --> 00:22:18.036 line:0%
(bell tolling)

00:22:18.069 --> 00:22:22.073 line:0%
LAURA GRUESER: Here in
our little neck of the woods,

00:22:22.106 --> 00:22:23.908
you can just look around

00:22:23.941 --> 00:22:28.513
and see that we show love
to each other in our area

00:22:28.546 --> 00:22:30.615
with food.

00:22:30.648 --> 00:22:31.683
That's what we do.

00:22:31.716 --> 00:22:36.421
We get together-- churches,

00:22:36.454 --> 00:22:39.290
baby showers,
bridal showers, birthdays--

00:22:39.323 --> 00:22:41.426
we're always eating.

00:22:41.459 --> 00:22:45.530
When you come to our homes,
we say, "Come on in.

00:22:45.563 --> 00:22:47.465
Let me fix you
something to eat."

00:22:47.498 --> 00:22:50.835
It's how we were raised.

00:22:50.868 --> 00:22:54.806
We don't get together
unless there's food.

00:22:54.839 --> 00:22:59.077
And usually,
it's not really good choices.

00:22:59.110 --> 00:23:02.847
I'm Laura Grueser, and
I'm the community health worker,

00:23:02.880 --> 00:23:05.817
the lead, at the Meigs County
Health Department.

00:23:05.850 --> 00:23:08.653
♪ ♪

00:23:08.686 --> 00:23:12.857
I was diagnosed as being
pre-diabetic in 2012.

00:23:12.890 --> 00:23:15.360
I didn't understand really
what the big deal was.

00:23:15.393 --> 00:23:19.831
It wasn't until I started
doing all the research,

00:23:19.864 --> 00:23:22.200
and I thought,
"Why shouldn't I use

00:23:22.233 --> 00:23:24.169
"this knowledge that I've got?

00:23:24.202 --> 00:23:27.872
"I can't teach somebody else
to live a healthier life

00:23:27.905 --> 00:23:31.576
"and come home and eat
a bag of potato chips.

00:23:31.609 --> 00:23:34.379 line:0%
That's not right,
I can't do that."

00:23:34.412 --> 00:23:37.916 line:0%
And so to live as an example
for my patients,

00:23:37.949 --> 00:23:40.752
my husband and I made
the final decision

00:23:40.785 --> 00:23:43.688
to really get on board
and start eating healthier.

00:23:43.721 --> 00:23:47.125
I'm able to take that back
to my patients

00:23:47.158 --> 00:23:48.326
and say, "It really does work.

00:23:48.359 --> 00:23:49.894
"It's evidence-based.

00:23:49.927 --> 00:23:51.563
"You really can do something

00:23:51.596 --> 00:23:54.032
about controlling
your own diabetes."

00:23:54.065 --> 00:23:56.801
And then they feel like,
you know,

00:23:56.834 --> 00:23:58.703
"If she can do it,
I can do this."

00:24:00.471 --> 00:24:03.708
NARRATOR: Meigs County, Ohio,
is in Appalachia,

00:24:03.741 --> 00:24:05.910
where diabetes rates

00:24:05.943 --> 00:24:08.446
rise well above the
national average of ten percent,

00:24:08.479 --> 00:24:11.282
as high as 15% or 16%.

00:24:11.315 --> 00:24:16.521
Most of the diabetes here
is type 2.

00:24:16.554 --> 00:24:19.123 line:0%
One of the big things
in Meigs County

00:24:19.156 --> 00:24:21.893 line:0%
is the pride of the people here
and the independence.

00:24:21.926 --> 00:24:27.265
It's very, very hard
for proud people to say,

00:24:27.298 --> 00:24:31.069
"I can't do this,
I need some help."

00:24:31.102 --> 00:24:33.104
And so I tell them, "Please,
just give me three months.

00:24:33.137 --> 00:24:35.306
"Give me three months
out of your life,

00:24:35.339 --> 00:24:37.976
"and listen to what I'm saying,
and get with this program.

00:24:38.009 --> 00:24:40.411
"If it doesn't work,

00:24:40.444 --> 00:24:41.713
"and you don't see any changes
in three months,

00:24:41.746 --> 00:24:43.281
"I'll leave you alone.

00:24:43.314 --> 00:24:44.849
And you can go on."

00:24:44.882 --> 00:24:46.685
No one has ever done that.

00:24:47.685 --> 00:24:50.855
Statistics show
that rural communities

00:24:50.888 --> 00:24:54.626
have a higher incidence
of diabetes

00:24:54.659 --> 00:24:58.096
than more of
a metropolitan area.

00:24:58.129 --> 00:25:01.966
And they... one of the
reasons that surprised me

00:25:01.999 --> 00:25:04.435
was because there's not enough
education out there

00:25:04.468 --> 00:25:07.105
to actually tell people

00:25:07.138 --> 00:25:09.140
something that I take
for granted.

00:25:09.173 --> 00:25:11.309
- Looks like cucumber.

00:25:11.342 --> 00:25:13.645
GRUESER: I had
a patient yesterday

00:25:13.678 --> 00:25:17.048
who had never, he nor his wife
had ever had a zucchini.

00:25:17.081 --> 00:25:20.885
I've been going into their home
for eight months.

00:25:20.918 --> 00:25:22.420
So yesterday, they had zucchini
for the first time.

00:25:22.453 --> 00:25:24.289
So, that's kind of
exciting to me.

00:25:24.322 --> 00:25:26.858
Cook it on high
for four to six hours.

00:25:26.891 --> 00:25:28.860
♪ ♪

00:25:28.893 --> 00:25:32.096
CABALLERO: Type 2 diabetes
is closely linked

00:25:32.129 --> 00:25:34.432
to the presence
of overweight or obesity,

00:25:34.465 --> 00:25:37.402
because the more fat
we have in our body,

00:25:37.435 --> 00:25:39.871
the more release of substances

00:25:39.904 --> 00:25:45.076 line:0%
that limit the ability
of insulin to do its job.

00:25:45.109 --> 00:25:48.713
This is what we call
insulin resistance.

00:25:48.746 --> 00:25:52.216
GRUESER: You can just
look around and see

00:25:52.249 --> 00:25:56.654
that there are so many people
who are suffering from obesity.

00:25:56.687 --> 00:25:59.257
So many people are, are
walking around

00:25:59.290 --> 00:26:02.360
with a bottle of Mountain Dew
in their hands.

00:26:02.393 --> 00:26:06.097
