that he was doing this.

01:03:09.852 --> 01:03:11.220
I think he was enjoying

01:03:11.253 --> 01:03:14.857
his, his freedom of living
on his own for the first time,

01:03:14.890 --> 01:03:18.127
so, I, I think that's
why he didn't ask for help.

01:03:21.096 --> 01:03:23.532
I don't think he knew

01:03:23.565 --> 01:03:27.169
that not taking
the required amount of insulin

01:03:27.202 --> 01:03:29.071
would lead to death.

01:03:29.104 --> 01:03:31.707
♪ ♪

01:03:31.740 --> 01:03:35.878
It was absolutely horrifying.

01:03:35.911 --> 01:03:39.282
♪ ♪

01:03:43.252 --> 01:03:45.488 line:0%
This is hard.

01:03:46.989 --> 01:03:51.293
I just miss my son.

01:03:51.326 --> 01:03:55.097
I think we all would be doing
anything to get our son back,

01:03:55.130 --> 01:03:57.132
our brother back.

01:03:57.165 --> 01:03:59.969
♪ ♪

01:04:00.002 --> 01:04:03.505
BRITTANY:
That week and after that moment,

01:04:03.538 --> 01:04:07.176
I mean, it changed us all
forever.

01:04:07.209 --> 01:04:10.312
(sighs)

01:04:10.345 --> 01:04:12.681
NICOLE SMITH-HOLT:
It still really sometimes

01:04:12.714 --> 01:04:14.817
doesn't feel real.

01:04:14.850 --> 01:04:16.218
- (breathes deeply)

01:04:16.251 --> 01:04:19.855
NICOLE SMITH-HOLT: It feels like
maybe Alec is just on vacation.

01:04:19.888 --> 01:04:24.093
And then there's moments
where I wake up,

01:04:24.126 --> 01:04:27.329
and I'm, like, "My son is gone.

01:04:27.362 --> 01:04:29.899
I'm not going to see him
anymore."

01:04:33.068 --> 01:04:35.070
CLOSE: There shouldn't be
any question

01:04:35.103 --> 01:04:36.438
about whether insulin
is a human right.

01:04:36.471 --> 01:04:37.640 line:0%
It obviously is.

01:04:37.673 --> 01:04:39.575 line:0%
Everybody in the world
should have access

01:04:39.608 --> 01:04:40.976 line:0%
to exactly how much they need.

01:04:41.009 --> 01:04:44.113
And if you can't pay
for insulin,

01:04:44.146 --> 01:04:47.182
you're back where we were
before Banting and Best--

01:04:47.215 --> 01:04:49.985 line:0%
you die.

01:04:50.018 --> 01:04:51.420 line:0%
BRITTANY:
So, this is the memorial garden

01:04:51.453 --> 01:04:55.324 line:0%
that we created
in honor of Alec.

01:04:55.357 --> 01:05:00.863
And we will keep fighting
in his honor, in his memory.

01:05:04.299 --> 01:05:06.468
SAINI:
Imagine yourself being a citizen

01:05:06.501 --> 01:05:08.337
in a town in the desert
where there's no water

01:05:08.370 --> 01:05:10.806
for hundreds and hundreds
and hundreds of miles,

01:05:10.839 --> 01:05:14.109
and the only way
you can get water is

01:05:14.142 --> 01:05:16.512
by going out and purchasing it.

01:05:16.545 --> 01:05:19.048
And imagine if there were
a handful of companies

01:05:19.081 --> 01:05:21.550
in that town
that were selling water,

01:05:21.583 --> 01:05:23.352
and they had
a monopoly on water.

01:05:23.385 --> 01:05:27.323
Well, the entire community
of people with diabetes

01:05:27.356 --> 01:05:31.126
is in that boat.

01:05:31.159 --> 01:05:36.933
In 1996, insulin cost $21.

01:05:38.233 --> 01:05:42.838 line:0%
20 years later,
it cost $255.

01:05:42.871 --> 01:05:44.073 line:0%
You have to ask yourself,

01:05:44.106 --> 01:05:46.875 line:0%
"Why has the price
been going up?"

01:05:46.908 --> 01:05:48.978 line:0%
So, what you get is pricing

01:05:49.011 --> 01:05:53.182
that reflects the power of the
people selling the product

01:05:53.215 --> 01:05:55.017
and the lack of power
of the people

01:05:55.050 --> 01:05:56.785
who absolutely need the product.

01:05:56.818 --> 01:05:59.621
The pharmaceutical companies,

01:05:59.654 --> 01:06:01.824
the big three
that manufacture insulin--

01:06:01.857 --> 01:06:06.729
that's Eli Lilly,
Novo Nordisk, and Sanofi--

01:06:06.762 --> 01:06:10.065
if you look
at the reported revenues

01:06:10.098 --> 01:06:13.068 line:0%
from these companies
on their insulin products,

01:06:13.101 --> 01:06:17.506 line:0%
now globally, they're up
in the tens of billions.

01:06:17.539 --> 01:06:19.074 line:0%
But you still hear
story after story

01:06:19.107 --> 01:06:20.743 line:0%
of patients who are rationing.
- Yeah.

01:06:20.776 --> 01:06:21.944 line:0%
- Patients who are harmed

01:06:21.977 --> 01:06:24.213 line:0%
because they can't afford
their insulin.

01:06:24.246 --> 01:06:25.547 line:0%
How do you make sure
every patient

01:06:25.580 --> 01:06:26.949 line:0%
can get the medicine they need?

01:06:26.982 --> 01:06:29.084 line:0%
- Yeah, well, we're, you know,
deeply bothered by that.

01:06:29.117 --> 01:06:30.886 line:0%
The facts you lay out are true.

01:06:30.919 --> 01:06:32.087 line:0%
The list prices have gone up.

01:06:32.120 --> 01:06:35.224 line:0%
Our net pricing is
basically flat since 2009.

01:06:35.257 --> 01:06:36.759 line:0%
Where's all that money
going in the middle?

01:06:36.792 --> 01:06:39.161 line:0%
It's going to negotiators
in the middle,

01:06:39.194 --> 01:06:40.429 line:0%
but not to patients,

01:06:40.462 --> 01:06:42.598 line:0%
who are increasingly
subjected to the list price.

01:06:42.631 --> 01:06:44.166 line:0%
And they have to make choices
like that

01:06:44.199 --> 01:06:46.101 line:0%
that they shouldn't
have to make.

01:06:46.134 --> 01:06:47.503 line:0%
NARRATOR:
"Negotiators in the middle"

01:06:47.536 --> 01:06:50.973 line:0%
refers
to pharmacy benefits managers,

01:06:51.006 --> 01:06:53.642 line:0%
a key part
of the drug pricing system.

01:06:53.675 --> 01:06:57.346 line:0%
As the insulin manufacturers
explained to Congress,

01:06:57.379 --> 01:07:00.516 line:0%
they set the list prices
for insulin.

01:07:00.549 --> 01:07:04.620 line:0%
But then pharmacy benefits
managers negotiate rebates

01:07:04.653 --> 01:07:08.390 line:0%
that are supposed
to lower consumer costs.

01:07:08.423 --> 01:07:10.826 line:0%
Despite the investment
that we make in rebates,

01:07:10.859 --> 01:07:13.896 line:0%
some patients, including those
with insurance,

01:07:13.929 --> 01:07:15.497 line:0%
end up paying list price
or close to it

01:07:15.530 --> 01:07:18.033 line:0%
at the pharmacy counter.

01:07:18.066 --> 01:07:21.203 line:0%
As a manufacturer,
Novo Nordisk has no control

01:07:21.236 --> 01:07:22.704 line:0%
over what insurance...

01:07:22.737 --> 01:07:25.340 line:0%
what insured patients pay
at the pharmacy counter.

01:07:25.373 --> 01:07:29.178 line:0%
So despite this ever-increasing
rebates that we pay,

01:07:29.211 --> 01:07:31.914 line:0%
patients don't get the full
benefits of those rebates

01:07:31.947 --> 01:07:34.016 line:0%
at the pharmacy counter.

01:07:34.049 --> 01:07:35.884 line:0%
This needs to change.

01:07:35.917 --> 01:07:39.455 line:0%
Patients are rightfully angry
about rising out-of-pocket costs

01:07:39.488 --> 01:07:42.658 line:0%
for many medicines, and
we all have a responsibility

01:07:42.691 --> 01:07:46.261 line:0%
to address a system that is
clearly failing too many people.

01:07:46.294 --> 01:07:50.399 line:0%
NARRATOR: All three of the
manufacturers blamed the system,

01:07:50.432 --> 01:07:53.001 line:0%
not their list pricing.

01:07:53.034 --> 01:07:55.003 line:0%
SAINI:
So everybody's pointing fingers,

01:07:55.036 --> 01:07:56.939
and in that environment,

01:07:56.972 --> 01:07:59.108
it's easy to point a finger
at the PBMs,

01:07:59.141 --> 01:08:01.009
the pharmacy benefit managers,

01:08:01.042 --> 01:08:04.113
because they got plenty
to answer for.

01:08:04.146 --> 01:08:06.281
But the same is true of
the pharmaceutical agencies.

01:08:06.314 --> 01:08:09.318 line:0%
Eli Lilly tonight is planning
on selling a cheaper version

01:08:09.351 --> 01:08:12.788 line:0%
of its top-selling insulin,
Humalog.

01:08:12.821 --> 01:08:15.324 line:0%
The drug maker hopes this will
ease the financial strain

01:08:15.357 --> 01:08:16.692 line:0%
for patients.

01:08:16.725 --> 01:08:20.863 line:0%
But an advocacy group says
much bigger changes are needed.

01:08:20.896 --> 01:08:23.866 line:0%
NARRATOR: The manufacturers,
under public pressure,

01:08:23.899 --> 01:08:27.769 line:0%
have supported programs
to cap insulin costs.

01:08:27.802 --> 01:08:30.405 line:0%
But they're not
available to everyone.

01:08:30.438 --> 01:08:32.374 line:0%
And people without insurance,
like Alec,

01:08:32.407 --> 01:08:35.878
may still pay full list price.

01:08:35.911 --> 01:08:37.112
SAINI:
Pharmaceutical companies.

01:08:37.145 --> 01:08:39.882
It's their product,
it's their price,

01:08:39.915 --> 01:08:41.950
and it's their customers
that are dying

01:08:41.983 --> 01:08:43.785
'cause they can't afford
their product.

01:08:43.818 --> 01:08:45.487
That makes no sense.

01:08:45.520 --> 01:08:47.723
And I think it's
a matter of responsibility.

01:08:47.756 --> 01:08:50.425
Own up to what's going on.

01:08:50.458 --> 01:08:52.628
People who have no insurance,

01:08:52.661 --> 01:08:55.430
all sorts of people
fall through the cracks.

01:08:55.463 --> 01:09:00.602
These are casualties
of a broken system.

01:09:00.635 --> 01:09:01.970
♪ ♪

01:09:02.003 --> 01:09:03.605
NARRATOR:
In a broken system,

01:09:03.638 --> 01:09:06.441
it's even harder
to follow the rules.

01:09:06.474 --> 01:09:11.113
(music playing on speakers)

01:09:11.146 --> 01:09:12.814
LEE:
I mean, it feels great

01:09:12.847 --> 01:09:16.351
to be back in, in the,
in the studio,

01:09:16.384 --> 01:09:19.421
active, working
on good music again.

01:09:19.454 --> 01:09:21.423
Got some good news
from the doctor,

01:09:21.456 --> 01:09:26.161
saying I'm healing right,
everything's coming along.

01:09:26.194 --> 01:09:28.564 line:0%
Here I am with Dr. Schillinger
all excited,

01:09:28.597 --> 01:09:31.233 line:0%
talking about, "Man, it look
like everything is closed up."

01:09:31.266 --> 01:09:34.937 line:0%
And we felt a little bit
of an opening still,

01:09:34.970 --> 01:09:39.274
but, like he said, it's 80%
to 90% closed back, so...

01:09:39.307 --> 01:09:42.978
I'm not 100%,
but I'm getting close.

01:09:43.011 --> 01:09:45.681
So, it's definitely
a great feeling

01:09:45.714 --> 01:09:48.717
to be able to be back
doing what I love.

01:09:48.750 --> 01:09:50.986
♪ But I'm still out here ♪

01:09:51.019 --> 01:09:53.589
♪ Oh, my God,
I'm going crazy ♪

01:09:53.622 --> 01:09:56.725
♪ No way can I get left behind ♪

01:09:56.758 --> 01:09:58.627
♪ I'm going crazy ♪

01:09:58.660 --> 01:10:01.196
MAN: You better hope he doesn't
see you, see this video,

01:10:01.229 --> 01:10:02.931
because you've been standing up
this whole time.

01:10:02.964 --> 01:10:04.700
- Yeah, I know, man,
I'mma get in trouble,

01:10:04.733 --> 01:10:08.003
but at least he can see
I'm doing something positive

01:10:08.036 --> 01:10:10.872
and enjoying myself
while I'm doing it.

01:10:10.905 --> 01:10:13.875
(TV playing in background)

01:10:13.908 --> 01:10:15.177
LEE: While I'm at the house,

01:10:15.210 --> 01:10:17.212
doctor's orders
to stay off my foot,

01:10:17.245 --> 01:10:19.682
so it's like a bed rest thing.

01:10:22.484 --> 01:10:28.290
It's been challenging,
very challenging.

01:10:28.323 --> 01:10:31.159
And I'm kind of like
having that type of tug of war

01:10:31.192 --> 01:10:34.363
with wanting to be on my feet,

01:10:34.396 --> 01:10:37.466
but having to stay off of it,
you know?

01:10:37.499 --> 01:10:40.502
So, it's been a challenge,
but I'm maintaining,

01:10:40.535 --> 01:10:42.871
staying prayed up,
and I've been getting blessed.

01:10:49.878 --> 01:10:51.246
Hi, son.
- Hi.

01:10:51.279 --> 01:10:52.814
- How are you?
- Good.

01:10:52.847 --> 01:10:55.250
How was school today?
- Good.

01:10:55.283 --> 01:10:56.918
LEE: My son,
his name is Monteil.

01:10:56.951 --> 01:10:59.755
He's a junior,
has my whole name.

01:10:59.788 --> 01:11:04.226
His nickname is Lil Money,
everybody calls him Lil Money.

01:11:04.259 --> 01:11:07.229
What's up, fella?
- What's up?

01:11:07.262 --> 01:11:10.465
- Not much--
Daddy just chilling.

01:11:10.498 --> 01:11:11.733
What's wrong?

01:11:11.766 --> 01:11:13.135
- I was praying

01:11:13.168 --> 01:11:15.270
that you wouldn't have
to get your toe cut off.

01:11:15.303 --> 01:11:17.339
- Yeah, it did.
- And my prayer came true.

01:11:17.372 --> 01:11:19.041
- Yeah, see, that was good.

01:11:19.074 --> 01:11:21.310
Daddy glad you was able to pray
for me, too,

01:11:21.343 --> 01:11:23.111
because I was scared.

01:11:23.144 --> 01:11:25.514
That's what my main worry is,

01:11:25.547 --> 01:11:27.449
is for you to do good in school.

01:11:27.482 --> 01:11:28.917
- And play sports.

01:11:28.950 --> 01:11:31.253
- And also take care
of yourself.

01:11:31.286 --> 01:11:33.455
- And then follow my dreams?
- Yep.

01:11:33.488 --> 01:11:36.191
And to take of yourself,
because health is wealth,

01:11:36.224 --> 01:11:39.661
and Daddy don't want you to be
sick like me,

01:11:39.694 --> 01:11:41.330
with this disease that I got,

01:11:41.363 --> 01:11:43.765
so you got to..
- I'm not eating too much sugar.

01:11:43.798 --> 01:11:46.401
- And you got to eat
your vegetables and drink milk.

01:11:46.434 --> 01:11:48.837
And drink a lot of water,
so your body

01:11:48.870 --> 01:11:50.472
and your bones can be strong.

01:11:52.841 --> 01:11:54.443
LEE:
My son, I love him to death.

01:11:54.476 --> 01:11:56.578
He's, like, my whole world.

01:11:56.611 --> 01:11:58.413
So I'm talking to him

01:11:58.446 --> 01:12:03.151
about not eating so much candy
and the sweet stuff

01:12:03.184 --> 01:12:06.988
that could build up and might
make you feel good now,

01:12:07.021 --> 01:12:11.060
but affects your body later-type
stuff, so he's learning.

01:12:15.296 --> 01:12:20.302
Let's see, can Daddy make one,
see do I still got it?

01:12:20.335 --> 01:12:21.737
Uh-oh, too short.

01:12:21.770 --> 01:12:27.409
LEE: He's kind of alert
now to what's going on.

01:12:27.442 --> 01:12:28.443
Look at that!

01:12:28.476 --> 01:12:31.380
I'm flat, son, there I go.

01:12:39.087 --> 01:12:41.223
Monteil, at really
the prime of his life,

01:12:41.256 --> 01:12:44.359
at the age of 36, almost 37,

01:12:44.392 --> 01:12:47.829
he's facing a really
big challenge,

01:12:47.862 --> 01:12:49.631
which is,
is he going to lose his foot?

01:12:49.664 --> 01:12:51.299
LEE: Look,
here's the famous guy.

01:12:51.332 --> 01:12:54.269
SCHILLINGER: You feeling me?

01:12:54.302 --> 01:12:55.270
Hey, buddy.
- How you doing, Doc?

01:12:55.303 --> 01:12:57.139
- Good to see you.
- You, too.

01:12:59.140 --> 01:13:01.109
Tell me about... the last time,

01:13:01.142 --> 01:13:02.577
we talked about
the insulin, right?

01:13:02.610 --> 01:13:04.646
- Yeah, I need,
I need more pens, too,

01:13:04.679 --> 01:13:07.549
and I think I just dropped
the two, last two I had

01:13:07.582 --> 01:13:09.284
in my Uber, when I jumped out.

01:13:09.317 --> 01:13:11.086 line:0%
- Oh, that's not good.
- I know.

01:13:11.119 --> 01:13:13.522 line:0%
- That's not good, 'cause
they're not going to fill that.

01:13:13.555 --> 01:13:16.057 line:0%
'Cause that's expensive.
But we'll try.

01:13:16.090 --> 01:13:19.127
Just to be frank with you,
I love you,

01:13:19.160 --> 01:13:22.798
but we're, we didn't make any
progress since the last visit.

01:13:22.831 --> 01:13:24.733
You didn't pick up
your cholesterol medicine.

01:13:24.766 --> 01:13:25.934
- Yeah, I know.

01:13:25.967 --> 01:13:27.335
- You didn't change
your insulin.

01:13:27.368 --> 01:13:29.404
I'm not, I'm not scolding you.
- I know.

01:13:29.437 --> 01:13:31.807
- What I'm doing is,
I'm just saying realities.

01:13:31.840 --> 01:13:35.010
- I'm thinking about personally
just changing my diet.

01:13:35.043 --> 01:13:38.347
I was about to fast for 30 days.
- Ooh.

01:13:40.448 --> 01:13:41.650
What do you mean by fasting?

01:13:41.683 --> 01:13:44.252
- I'm trying to just...
water and juice.

01:13:44.285 --> 01:13:47.889
- Okay, so that will kill you.

01:13:47.922 --> 01:13:49.858
That's off the table, okay,
that, this is...

01:13:49.891 --> 01:13:51.827
- That'll kill me?
- Yes, that will kill you.

01:13:51.860 --> 01:13:52.861
And I'm not joking.

01:13:52.894 --> 01:13:55.564
You have diabetes, okay?

01:13:55.597 --> 01:13:57.632
You need to be on insulin.

01:13:57.665 --> 01:14:00.035
Your problem is
the kind of food you're eating.

01:14:00.068 --> 01:14:01.269
- Yeah.
- But I think that's probably

01:14:01.302 --> 01:14:02.838
because of the income problem
you have, too.

01:14:02.871 --> 01:14:04.739
- Yeah, right.
- So what I would say is,

01:14:04.772 --> 01:14:07.275
let's get you some food
and some income.

01:14:07.308 --> 01:14:09.444
And then you can make
some better choices

01:14:09.477 --> 01:14:11.847
around things that will
actually make your body healthy.

01:14:11.880 --> 01:14:13.849
But I pray you don't fast.

01:14:13.882 --> 01:14:16.451
We want you making slow,
careful adjustments

01:14:16.484 --> 01:14:18.453
at the right time
in the right way.

01:14:18.486 --> 01:14:19.621
Okay?
- Okay

01:14:19.654 --> 01:14:21.990
Don't go be on a superhero
in that regard.

01:14:22.023 --> 01:14:23.292
- No, no, no.

01:14:25.126 --> 01:14:29.264
I remember a lot of days, I was
just, like, ready to give up.

01:14:29.297 --> 01:14:30.499
And I was, like...
- I know you were.

01:14:30.532 --> 01:14:32.567
- I can't give up--
I had a talk with my son

01:14:32.600 --> 01:14:34.769
that kind of tripped me out,
too, like.

01:14:34.802 --> 01:14:38.940
Just to let me know that it's
on his mind as well as mine.

01:14:38.973 --> 01:14:41.810
When I see that he's concerned,

01:14:41.843 --> 01:14:45.881
it just make me
want to fight harder.

01:14:45.914 --> 01:14:50.418
Pretty much.

01:14:50.451 --> 01:14:52.120
Yep.

