an artificial pancreas.

01:27:28.876 --> 01:27:32.913
NARRATOR: It's what Ed Damiano
and other scientists

01:27:32.946 --> 01:27:35.016
have been working towards
for decades.

01:27:35.049 --> 01:27:37.952
♪ ♪

01:27:37.985 --> 01:27:42.256
ED: The bionic pancreas
really builds on the shoulders

01:27:42.289 --> 01:27:43.924 line:0%
of, really, decades
of technology development

01:27:43.957 --> 01:27:45.459 line:0%
in medical devices.

01:27:45.492 --> 01:27:51.032 line:0%
It comes from the synthesis
of continuous glucose monitors,

01:27:51.065 --> 01:27:55.002 line:0%
from insulin pumps,
from smartphones,

01:27:55.035 --> 01:27:58.339
and it's the integration
of those three technologies

01:27:58.372 --> 01:28:00.107
that makes a system
which is really better

01:28:00.140 --> 01:28:02.610
than the sum of its parts.

01:28:02.643 --> 01:28:04.912
It's basically got automated
decision-making software

01:28:04.945 --> 01:28:07.214
that determines how much drug
to deliver

01:28:07.247 --> 01:28:09.817
to the person with type 1
diabetes every five minutes.

01:28:09.850 --> 01:28:13.821
It makes 288 decisions every day
that you no longer have to make.

01:28:13.854 --> 01:28:16.557
(applause)

01:28:16.590 --> 01:28:19.093
So, David is a teenage boy.

01:28:19.126 --> 01:28:21.896
Now, I was a teenage boy,

01:28:21.929 --> 01:28:24.465
so I, you know,
I know whereof I speak.

01:28:24.498 --> 01:28:26.500
And teenage boys are not human.

01:28:26.533 --> 01:28:29.203
(laughter)

01:28:29.236 --> 01:28:35.343
Teenage boys are highly complex
multicellular organisms at best.

01:28:35.376 --> 01:28:38.846
They're a disconnected mass
of excitable cells,

01:28:38.879 --> 01:28:41.015
but they're a danger
to themselves,

01:28:41.048 --> 01:28:43.951
as I was many times over, again.

01:28:43.984 --> 01:28:47.888
David once nearly stabbed
himself with a toothbrush.

01:28:47.921 --> 01:28:49.623
Imagine that for just a moment.

01:28:49.656 --> 01:28:52.760
All of the worries and the fear
of type 1 diabetes,

01:28:52.793 --> 01:28:54.395
and we almost lost him

01:28:54.428 --> 01:28:57.198
to stabbing, self-stabbing,
by a toothbrush.

01:28:57.231 --> 01:28:59.500
I feel like as long as he's
with us, he'll be safe,

01:28:59.533 --> 01:29:01.969
but the worry is,
when he leaves home,

01:29:02.002 --> 01:29:05.406
when he's on his own,
when he's in college,

01:29:05.439 --> 01:29:06.707
and he's got to,

01:29:06.740 --> 01:29:08.609
he's got to check
those blood sugars at night.

01:29:08.642 --> 01:29:09.610
Will he wake up at night?

01:29:09.643 --> 01:29:11.345
Will he wake up
to see another day?

01:29:11.378 --> 01:29:15.983
I... we, we cannot, we must not
get that phone call.

01:29:17.985 --> 01:29:21.455
The bionic pancreas is
a sturdy bridge to a cure.

01:29:21.488 --> 01:29:23.190
It is...

01:29:23.223 --> 01:29:26.527
HURLEY: I'm glad to see Ed
with other people

01:29:26.560 --> 01:29:28.262
all in a race

01:29:28.295 --> 01:29:32.733
to bring the artificial pancreas
to the market,

01:29:32.766 --> 01:29:35.569
because the more players,
the better the odds

01:29:35.602 --> 01:29:38.105
that someone will come up
with the right system.

01:29:38.138 --> 01:29:40.307
"The race for the best
closed-loop system"--

01:29:40.340 --> 01:29:41.575
are you kidding, the best?

01:29:41.608 --> 01:29:43.043
I mean, the best is
going to depend on,

01:29:43.076 --> 01:29:44.044
what do you need,
or what do you need,

01:29:44.077 --> 01:29:45.646
or what do I need, right?

01:29:45.679 --> 01:29:47.915
It's not the right question
to ask at all,

01:29:47.948 --> 01:29:49.817
because it's not going
to be just one system.

01:29:49.850 --> 01:29:53.954
We want many, many closed-loop
systems to do well,

01:29:53.987 --> 01:29:55.156
and they're going to do well.

